
 Logic bugs can cause DBMSs to silently produce incorrect results for a given query, posing significant threats to software reliability and remaining challenging to detect. Join is a fundamental operation in DBMSs, enabling the combination of data from multiple tables; however, due to its complexity, it is also susceptible to logic bugs. Existing works detect logic bugs in join optimizations by altering query hints and system variables to alter the optimizer's choice of execution plans. However, these approaches struggle to detect logic bugs when query hints or system variables fail to influence the optimizer's behavior, or when the logic bugs reside in join implementation code that is unrelated to optimization. In this paper, we present
